Uber just lost a $2.8 billiion lawsuit in the UK and will have to re-classify its UK drivers as employees. I thought this negative news would blow over in a few weeks since Uber made a profit in the third quarter and the UK accounted for a relatively small percentage of its total revenue in 2020, Europe, the Middle East and Africa accounted for $2.09 billiion out of $11.15 billion total revenue. I could not find a further breakdown to just Europe, but I will assume at least 2/3's of the revenue came from Europe. If so, only about 10 percent of total revenue came from Europe and of course, less came from just the UK, maybe three to eight percent of Ubers' total revenue.

It looks like Uber's recent price decline had as much to do with losing a $2.8 billion lawsuit and the UK requiring the re-clasification of it's drivers as it did with the new covid variant. Uber made a operating profit in the third quarter for the first time--and during covid. So, I think the price will likely increase as the shock of losing such a large case and the fear of the omnicon variant decline.

Uber actualmente capitaliza cerca de 113 millones de dólares. A fines del 2020 su capitalización bordaba los 50 millones de dólares, es decir, aumentó cerca del doble, después de un complicado año de pandemia. En base a la masiva vacunación que se está produciendo en todo el mundo contra el coronavirus, los especialistas aproximan que en EEUU, para mitad de año (2021), debería estar la mitad de la población vacunada. En Chile, para Julio-Agosto de este año, debiesemos tener cerca de un 70% de la población vacunada. Esto claramente incidirá en la libertad de las personas, permitiendo mayor movilización luego del fin de las cuarentenas y la vuelta a la vida "normal", y por lo tanto, mayor uso de apliciones como Uber. Es por esto, que creo que será muy poco probable que su capitalización baje con respecto a la actual, sabiendo que todo apunta a que se termine el coronavirus. Tiene muchas posibilidades de aumentar, debido a que si todo funciona correctamente con el virus, Uber podría seguir con el crecimiento que viene desde fines del año pasado (cerca de un 50%). También podría mantenerse por que aún hay mucha incertidumbre mundial en muchos países, con las vacunas, nuevas sepas, y todo tipo de cosas que puedan hacernos volver a las cuarentenas, pero irían compensando los países que no estén confinados.

Según el sitio macrotrends (https://www.macrotrends.net/stocks/charts/UBER/uber-technologies/market-cap), el cual ilustra gráficamente la capitalización de Uber en el último año, actualmente uber capitaliza alrededor de 100 billones de dólares, lo cual representa casi el doble de lo que se logró en diciembre del 2020. Es imposible para mí no hacer el vínculo de estos números con el porcentaje de vacunación que existe hoy a nivel mundial contra el Covid-19. Podemos tomar la muestra de Estados Unidos, país que ha tenido un buen desempeño en cuanto este tema, lo cual representaría un escenario mas bien optimista en comparación con la situación mundial. Además, Uber se encuentra presente en este país desde hace alrededor de 12 años, entonces podemos utilizarlo como ejemplo.

Uber certainly has been on a wild ride since going public in May 2019. The IPO set the valuation at about $82 billion. The market cap on Dec 31, 2019, saw that number shrink when Uber had a market cap of about $51 billion following a decline in the stock post-IPO. The first half of 2020 saw a massive decline in the stock down to a low of $14. However, the second-half rebound has shot the stock up to all-time new highs. The closing market cap for 2020 saw Uber pass its initial valuation with a market cap of about $89 billion. That has since grown to right around $104 billion currently. The daily market cap average since the IPO has been about $65 billion, so it would appear Uber is currently trending up.

Uber's current market capitalization could be inflated or it may plateau at its current level. It is possible that Uber's market capitalization will increase significantly to $125 or $150 billion but it is unlikely. This will need to be revisited throughout the year since a lot can change if Uber introduces new technology, wins/loses lawsuits, or if new competitors enter the market.

Uber is false prophet and essentially premised on a few major things. 1. Regulatory arbitrage. It makes money by avoiding things like payroll taxes and having people working for it seen as temporary contractors. More and more governments are getting frustrated by this, especially when they are going to be scrambling for increased taxes soon. 2. Ubers stock is frothy and just over 100 billion at the moment, a lot of that is driven by hot cash floating around the market and the name recognition that Uber has - the silly money if you will. That will drop it below 100 billion when there is bad economic or other news in the next year. 3. Uber is only worth a high price if it has a plan to get rid of one of it's major costs (drivers). It doesn't. It's self driving R&D has been a shambles. It has little or no hope of being able to develop the tech to do that. Tesla and the others are so much further ahead. Uber is also too big to be bought out by a big car company.

Uber's current market capitalization reflects the impact of COVID-19 on travel generally and specifically people's use of public transportation and Uber. In 6 months, it is probable that more than 50% of the population of the US will have received the COVID-19 vaccine, this likely will lead to surge in travel and people going out, which will impact positively Uber's market capitalization.
